article.headline: Utah 74, Wyoming 49
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Before facing Utah on Saturday, Wyoming wasn't worried if reserve forward Jonas Langvad got some open shots. After all, the sophomore from Denmark hadn't scored any more than 11 points in his college career and was averaging just 4.1 points a game this season. But Langvad made the Cowboys regret it afterward. Langvad hit 7-of-11 shots, including 4-of-7 3-pointers, in leading Utah to an easy 74-49 victory over Wyoming and to its ninth consecutive win. Bryant Markson added 15 points, Tim Drisdom 13, and Andrew Bogut 12 for the Utes (14-3 overall, 2-0 Mountain West Conference). Marc Jackson recorded 10 assists. Utah scored the game's first 16 points -- half of them by Markson, who had 11 points in the first half -- and the Utes never faced a serious challenge the rest of the contest. "Up 16-nothing ... we just got off to a great start and just kept playing hard on defense," Langvad said. Wyoming, which missed its first 10 shots and hit just 28.6 percent from the field in the first half, didn't get on the scoreboard until Chris Anderson hit one of two free throws at the 10:18 mark. Utah coach Ray Giacoletti said his team succeeded in getting Wyoming's offense out of rhythm early in the game. "That was important for us to get off to a good start, obviously, on the road," he said. Wyoming (8-7, 0-2) would get no closer than 13 points the rest of the game as Utah led 32-16 at halftime and went ahead by as many as 32 points in the second half. "We went out there and embarrassed ourselves," said Jay Straight, who led the Cowboys with 12 points -- six below his average. Kevin Lewis had 10, all in the second half after not playing in the first half. "We played the first nine minutes without scoring and played terrible defense -- that was it right there," Lewis said. The Cowboys finished the game shooting 37 percent from the field (18-of-49), while Utah made 59 percent (27-46). Utah also outrebounded Wyoming 35-22. "They scored like, I don't know 15 points in the last three minutes," Langvad said. "We just played great defense." Wyoming coach Steve McClain said his team succeeded in controlling Bogut and Jackson -- Utah's top two scores entering the game -- but Langvad and others stepped up their games. "We just have to put this one behind us," McClain said. "We have to get back at it tomorrow, get focused and prepare for BYU." Utah travels to Colorado State on Monday, while Wyoming hosts BYU.
